"Best By 05/28/2015.  Vertical bottle pour into a stout glass as directed by Left Hand Brewery.  Pour reveals cascades of beautiful purging nitrogen from bottom to top.  Head eventually grows to two fingers - it is quite dense and creamy looking and light khaki in color.  Light on the nose: Roasted malts, coffee bean, then chocolate milk.  Mouth feel is sort of light as soon as it enters the mouth, but the agitation of the nitrogen creates the illusion of a full bodied and very creamy stout.  I Could session this all day long at 6% ABV.  Taste is like the smell but more pronounced - roasted malts, chocolate milk, then light coffee bean/slight hop bitterness lingers for a little while.  Overall I'm very impressed, and I like the Nitro Milk Stout better than Left Hand's regular Milk Stout because it's so pretty to look at and it tastes creamier yet less filling."
